TSI results on Seroconverters

Andrea Brizzi

29 March 2022

This html file summarises the results of the latest Time Since Infection analysis, produced on

Phyloanalysis details.

The phyloanalysis was performed using Xiayoue run in the RCCS deep analyses directory in the subfolder:

19037_phsc_phscrelationships_seed_42_blacklist_report_TRUE_distance_threshold_1_min_reads_per_host_1_multinomial_TRUE_outgroup_name_BFR83HXB2_LAI_IIIB_BRUK03455_output_nexus_tree_TRUE_ratio_blacklist_threshold_0005_skip_summary_graph_TRUE

The shell script mentioned below can all be found at:

/rds/general/project/ratmann_deepseq_analyses/live/PANGEA2_RCCS1519_UVRI/19037_phsc_work

We tried to follow instructions for IQTREE and for analyse_trees.R as close as possible. However, we have not confirmed yet whether the options of phyloscanner_make_trees.py are coherent with Tanya’s paper.

Sample selection

Same sample as in the previous Phyloscanner analysis set up by Xiaoyue, whose aim was to determine phylogenetically close pairs. We know that the administration of ART may slow down the in-host viral evolution, so maybe restrict the selection to all PANGEA_ID samples that were collected on date of first diagnosis? On the other hand, we may assume that individuals with multiple measurements are not on ART, as this would imply undectable virus?

Further, the prefixes for the file names sent by Tanya and the ones we use are different. In particular there is a WithHXB2 chunk which we do not have. Is this important?

# File prefixes we use:
J114980R19_PanMix1-E1A1L1P1S1C1R1_remap.bam

# File prefixes sent by Tanya:
J114980R19_PanMix1-E1A1L1P1S1C1R1_remap_BaseFreqs_WithHXB2.csv

IQTREE

IQTREE was run on the treefiles generated by the make_deep_sequence_alignments.R step, with code in shell scripts prefixed by: srx.job* Treefiles may have 2 different types ofo prefixes, depending on whether excision was performed or not: ptyrX_InWindow_(PositionsExcised_)Y_to_Z.v2. We were unsure on what to do about the -starttree PARS option, as we did not find any info in the documentation. The options are:

Ours

iqtree \
-s ptyr1_InWindow_PositionsExcised_800_to_1049_v2.fasta \
-m GTR+F+R6 \
-seed 42 \
-pre ptyr1_InWindow_PositionsExcised_800_to_1049_v2

Tanya’s

iqtree \
-s ${InputDir}/${InputFile} \
-m GTR+F+R6 \
-starttree PARS \
-pre iqtree_bestTree.InWindow_${w}

Lele’s

iqtree \
-s ../AlignedReads/AlignedReadsInWindow_PositionsExcised_${WINSTRING}.fasta \
-m GTR+F+R6
-nt 1 \ # Numer of corse, should be inconsequential
-pre iqtree_${WINSTRING} \

This implementation should be ‘equivalent’.

Analyse Trees

Finally, Phyloscanner is used to analyse trees, with code generated by shell scripts prefixed by phsc*.

Ours

/rds/general/user/xx4515/home/phyloscanner/phyloscanner_analyse_trees.R "/rds/general/project/ratmann_deepseq_analyses/live/PANGEA2_RCCS1519_UVRI//19037_phsc_output/ptyr1_trees" ptyr1 s,15 \
--allowMultiTrans \
--distanceThreshold -1 \
--fileNameRegex "^(?:.*\D)?([0-9]+)_to_([0-9]+).*$" \
--minReadsPerHost 1 \
--minTipsPerHost 1 \
--multifurcationThreshold 1e-05 \
--multinomial \
--normRefFileName "~/phyloscanner/InfoAndInputs/HIV_DistanceNormalisationOverGenome.csv" \
--outgroupName "B.FR.83.HXB2_LAI_IIIB_BRU.K03455" \
--outputNexusTree \
--outputRDA \
--overwrite \
--parsimonyBlacklistK 15 \
--ratioBlacklistThreshold 0.005 \
--rawBlacklistThreshold 3 \
--readCountsMatterOnZeroLengthBranches \
--readCountsMatterOnZeroLengthBranches \
--seed 42 \
--skipSummaryGraph \
--tipRegex "^(.*)-fq[0-9]+_read_([0-9]+)_count_([0-9]+)$" \
--treeFileExtension ".treefile" \
--verbose 1

The differences btwn Tanya and Lele are in the outgroup name -og and in the NormRef file name -nr. I don t think these should matter too much.

Data

Info

Out of the 50 ptyr completed ptyr runs, HIV-phylo-TSI produced results for about 40 ptyr. Each of these contained between 60 and 100 individuals, and a total of 184 seroconverters (defined as having a non-NA firstpositive and lastnegative dates in the allhiv dataset + retrievable date of sample collection).

Epidemiological data provided us with:

  • the sampling_date (i.~e. the date of collection of the blood sample) and the seroconversion
  • the midpoint (i.~e. the average between the dates of last negative and first positive tests) and hence we could define the trueTSI as the difference between the above two quantities.

On the other hand HIV-phylo-TSI allowed us to estimated:

  • the predictedTSI as the central estimate of the algorithm in linear time.

Issues

Results

load(path.meta.data)
dsero <- fread(file.seroconverters)

cols <- c('date_last_negative', 'date_first_positive')
new_cols <- c('knownTSI_max', 'knownTSI_min')
dsero[, (new_cols) := lapply(.SD , function(x) (visit_dt - x)/365), .SDcols=cols ]

if(0)
{
        dsero[!is.na(knownTSI_max) & !is.na(knownTSI_min), mean(knownTSI_max - knownTSI_min > 5)]
        png("dserohist.png")
        hist(dsero[, knownTSI_max - knownTSI_min])
        dev.off()
}

The above definitions allow us to plot the bias in the estimates trueTSI - predictedTSI as a function of the trueTSI, similarly to Figure S8 in the paper. Below I compare the results obtained from our 2 analyses, as well as the results Tanya obtained on a batch from Rakai. In all cases, we see, to be overestimating TSI in chronic infections. However, in Tanya’s case the predictions correlate with the known values, while in our case this is not true (correlations are reported in the plot for individuals whose known TSI is smaller than 5 years). Further, since the seroconversion interval can be quite wide, I use colors to denote which imputed TSI fall between the last negative and the first positive dates.

Input-Output comparison with Tanya’s run

We also compared the input and output’s of HIV-phylo-TSI for our run, and for the run sent by Tanya. The objective was to see whether the predictions are similar, and whether the outputs of the different phyloscanner runs are consistent.

We see that we had some problems with the first run, but then most of these were solved. Still we are counting fewer tips across the 3 genes as compared to Tanya. This is probably due to our phyloscanner parameters, which exclude some tips based on QUALITY?

Also lrtt are not exactly identical but that may make sense: tent to underestimate gag, overestimate pol, and about right for gp120.

Second run

Fourth run
